04509nam a22006735i 9780271050584DE-B159720210526051534.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210526t20212011pau    fo  d z      eng d  a97802710505847 a10.1515/97802710505842doi  a(DE-B1597)584003  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 4aHQ1236.5.N5bG66 2011eb 7aPOL0040002bisacsh04a305.420972852231 aGonzález-Rivera, Victoria, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aBefore the Revolution :bWomen's Rights and Right-Wing Politics in Nicaragua, 1821-1979 /cVictoria González-Rivera. 1aUniversity Park, PA : bPenn State University Press, c[2021] 4c©2011  a1 online resource (256 p.) :b16 illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIllustration -- tPreface -- tAcknowledgments -- tAbbreviations -- tIntroduction -- t1 Feminism Before Somoza -- t2 From Feminism to Partisan Suffragist Politics -- t3 The Aftermath of Women's Suffrage -- t4 Somocista Women's Lives -- t5 The Activism and Legacy of Nicolasa Sevilla -- t6 Sex and Somocismo -- tConclusion -- tAppendix A: UMA Founding Members -- tAppendix B: Central Women's Committee Members -- tNotes -- tSelected Bibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThose who survived the brutal dictatorship of the Somoza family have tended to portray the rise of the women's movement and feminist activism as part of the overall story of the anti-Somoza resistance. But this depiction of heroic struggle obscures a much more complicated history. As Victoria González-Rivera reveals in this book, some Nicaraguan women expressed early interest in eliminating the tyranny of male domination, and this interest grew into full-fledged campaigns for female suffrage and access to education by the 1880s. By the 1920s a feminist movement had emerged among urban, middle-class women, and it lasted for two more decades until it was eclipsed in the 1950s by a nonfeminist movement of mainly Catholic, urban, middle-class and working-class women who supported the liberal, populist, patron-clientelistic regime of the Somozas in return for the right to vote and various economic, educational, and political opportunities. Counterintuitively, it was actually the Somozas who encouraged women's participation in the public sphere (as long as they remained loyal Somocistas). Their opponents, the Sandinistas and Conservatives, often appealed to women through their maternal identity. What emerges from this fine-grained analysis is a picture of a much more complex political landscape than that portrayed by the simplifying myths of current Nicaraguan historiography, and we can now see why and how the Somoza dictatorship did not endure by dint of fear and compulsion alone.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mai 2021) 0aFeminismxHistory. 0aWomenxPolitical activityxHistoryxNicaragua. 0aWomenxPolitical activityzNicaraguaxHistory. 0aWomenxSuffragexHistory. 0aWomen's rightsxHistory. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Civil Rights.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn State University Press Complete eBook-Package Pre-2014z978311074526940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780271050584423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780271050584.jpg  a978-3-11-074526-9  Penn State University Press Complete eBook-Package Pre-2014b2014  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK